#identify non-valid-UTF-8-characters in a string and delete them
review$ReviewText <- iconv(review$ReviewText, "UTF-8", "UTF-8",sub='')

#identify languages
review$language <- textcat(review$ReviewText)

#filter english review
review <-
  review %>%
  filter(language == "english")

Count data model

Poisson Regression

The simplest distribution used for modeling count data is the Poisson distribution with probability density function: \[f(y;\mu )=\frac{exp(-\mu)\cdot \mu^{y}}{y!}\] The canonical link is g(\(\mu\)) = log(\(\mu\)) resulting in a log-linear relationship between mean and linear predictor. In R, this can easily be specied in the glm() call just by setting family = poisson.

glm(formula, data, family = poisson, start = NULL, 
model = TRUE, y = TRUE, x = FALSE, ...)

Negative Binomial Regression

Another way of modeling over-dispersed count data is to assume a negative binomial (NB) distribution for \(y_{i}|x_{i}\) which can arise as a gamma mixture of Poisson distributions \[f(y;\mu,\theta )=\frac{\tau (y+\theta)}{\tau(\theta)}\cdot \frac{\mu^{y}\cdot\theta^{\theta}}{(\mu+\theta)^{y+\theta}}\] the function glm.nb() from the package MASS can give the result

glm.nb(formula, data, weights, start = NULL, 
       control = glm.control(...), method = "glm.fit",
       model = TRUE, x = FALSE, y = TRUE, contrasts = NULL, ...,
       init.theta, link = log)

Baseline Model

Regression without fixed effect

fit1= glm.nb(NumHelpful~
               AvgRatingStarsThisUser +
               Rating_Deviation +
               log(WC) +
               Not_Disclosure +
               women +
               MidAge +  
               OldAge,
              review,link = log)

Regression with fixed effect

fit2= glm.nb(NumHelpful~
               AvgRatingStarsThisUser +
               Rating_Deviation +
               log(WC)+ 
               Not_Disclosure +
               women +
               MidAge +  
               OldAge +
               HotelID+ 
               year,
             review,
             link = log)

Extension:Understanding the Relationships of Variables

Regression without control variables

model1 <- polr(factor(AvgRatingStarsThisUser) ~ sentiment,data = review,Hess = TRUE)

model2 <-lm(sentiment ~ factor(AvgRatingStarsThisUser),data = review)

Regression with control variables

model3 <- polr(factor(AvgRatingStarsThisUser) ~ 
                 sentiment + 
                 factor(HotelID) + 
                 year +
                 log(WC) + 
                 Not_Disclosure +
                 women +
                 MidAge +  
                 OldAge,data = review,Hess = TRUE)

model4 <-lm(sentiment ~ 
              factor(AvgRatingStarsThisUser) +
              factor(HotelID) + 
              year +
              log(WC) + 
              Not_Disclosure +
              women +
              MidAge +  
              OldAge,data = review)

output the results

stargazer(list(model1,model3, model2,model4),type = "text",omit = c("HotelID","year"))
